President Cyril Ramaphosa wants to deploy over 73,000 more soldiers to fight COVID-19. The new deployment will include medical and auxiliary staff. Meanwhile, the SAPS and SANDF have been accused of abusing their power. Gareth Newham from the Institute for Security Studies spoke to Jane Dutton. #Day28ofLockdown JOHANNESBURG - The South African Army, Air Force, Navy, and Medical Health Services reserves are being asked to confirm their availability. The SANDF needs their help to fight COVID-19. READ: Ramaphosa deploys more soldiers The Defence Force says it needs nurses, doctors, chefs, mechanics, engineers, and pilots. Those who are currently serving in the Reserve Force but who have not yet been called up have been asked to contact their units. They will form part of Operation Notlela. Reserves will be called up as and when required. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.